  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Capacity building for the care of &quot;Our Common House&quot; in vulnerable rural communities in Nicaragua</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In this project we will be working with our strategic partner, The Roncalli- John XXIII Association, who have nearly 60 years of experience promoting social justice to improve opportunities for some of the poorest people in Nicaragua. 
John XXIII has been working with agricultural cooperatives and promoting productive economic activities, raising awareness on environmental protection and care by working with local authorities and community members in disaster risk reduction as well. 
The project  will be implemented with men and women, boys and girls from rural communities in Ciudad Dar&#xED;o and Esquipulas and Terrabona which are based in the department of Matagalpa, face a multitude of challenges when trying to break free from the cycle of poverty. Located in the middle of the dry corridor, the area is vulnerable to drought. Targeting those vulnerable communities, we will address the following challenges that we have identified through in-depth analysis: There is insufficient awareness and skills to care for the environment &#x2013; perpetuating the cycle of poverty, further contributing to climate change, the impacts of which negatively impacts on their livelihoods. There is poor organisation and administrative management of cooperatives that have been formed and finally and most important, Women have limited access to fertile land and resources for production
The project aims to reach 730 more vulnerable community members (410 women) to adopt an integrated approach, in line with Pope Francis&#x2019; teachings (&#x2018;integral ecology&#x2019;), so John XXIII has great capacity that can challenge the root causes keeping the target communities living in poverty, address practices that are harmful to the environment, and promote equality of women. Through this we can ensure we address both the Cry of the Poor and the Earth. The total indirect target group will be 1,765 members of their families and wider community. We consider this three-year project will be the first phase of a process that will last for at least five years.</narrative>
  </description>
